The crash is caused by a double-free of `blob_t.name`.

The failing call stack stops in:

```c
static void destroy_blob(blob_t *b) {
    if (!b) return;
    free(b->name);          /* release the name buffer */
    free(b);
}
```

at `free(b->name)`, with AddressSanitizer reporting:

```text
Deallocation of freed memory
```

The important earlier code is in `load_blob`:

```c
static blob_t *load_blob(const char *name) {
    blob_t *b = (blob_t *)malloc(sizeof(*b));
    if (!b) return NULL;

    b->name = strdup(name);
    b->size = 0;

    if (!b->name) {
        free(b);
        return NULL;
    }

    /* Simulated recoverable parse error. */
    if (strlen(name) > 4) {
        free(b->name);      /* release the name on the recoverable error path */
        b->size = 0;
        return b;           /* hand the partially-initialised blob back */
    }

    b->size = strlen(b->name);
    return b;
}
```

`main` calls:

```c
blob_t *b = load_blob("abcdef");   /* triggers the recoverable error path */
...
destroy_blob(b);
```

The input string is `"abcdef"`, whose length is `6`, so this branch in `load_blob` executes:

```c
if (strlen(name) > 4) {
    free(b->name);
    b->size = 0;
    return b;
}
```

Program state walkthrough:

1. `main` calls:

   ```c
   load_blob("abcdef");
   ```

2. `load_blob` allocates the `blob_t` object:

   ```c
   b = malloc(sizeof(*b));
   ```

   At this point `b` is valid.

3. It duplicates the name:

   ```c
   b->name = strdup(name);
   ```

   Now `b->name` points to a separately allocated heap buffer containing `"abcdef"`.

4. It initializes:

   ```c
   b->size = 0;
   ```

5. Since `strlen("abcdef") > 4`, the recoverable error path runs:

   ```c
   free(b->name);
   b->size = 0;
   return b;
   ```

   After `free(b->name)`, the memory pointed to by `b->name` has been released, but `b->name` itself is not changed. It still contains the stale pointer value.

6. `load_blob` returns `b` to `main`.

   So in `main`, `b` is non-`NULL`, `b->size == 0`, and `b->name` is a dangling pointer.

7. `main` then calls:

   ```c
   destroy_blob(b);
   ```

8. `destroy_blob` does:

   ```c
   free(b->name);
   ```

   But `b->name` still contains the pointer that was already freed in `load_blob`. This is the second `free` of the same allocation, causing the reported crash.

The defect is that `load_blob` returns a partially initialized object whose ownership state is inconsistent: `b->name` no longer owns a live allocation, but the pointer field still looks non-`NULL`, so the destructor assumes it must free it.

There are two reasonable fixes.

Minimal local fix: after freeing `b->name` in the recoverable error path, set it to `NULL`.

```c
if (strlen(name) > 4) {
    free(b->name);
    b->name = NULL;
    b->size = 0;
    return b;
}
```

Because `free(NULL)` is defined to do nothing, `destroy_blob` can safely remain:

```c
free(b->name);
free(b);
```

That fixes the immediate double-free.

A more thorough root-cause fix is to make ownership semantics explicit and avoid returning an object whose owned fields have already been partially destroyed. If `load_blob` fails to produce a valid blob, it should either return `NULL` after freeing the whole object, or return an object in a fully consistent empty state.

For example, if the recoverable parse error means “no blob was loaded,” then `load_blob` should clean up completely and return `NULL`:

```c
if (strlen(name) > 4) {
    free(b->name);
    free(b);
    return NULL;
}
```

Then `main` already handles `NULL` safely because `destroy_blob(NULL)` is a no-op:

```c
destroy_blob(b);
```

Alternatively, if the intended API is to return an “empty blob” with `size == 0`, then the object must be returned in a valid destructible state:

```c
if (strlen(name) > 4) {
    free(b->name);
    b->name = NULL;
    b->size = 0;
    return b;
}
```

The key invariant should be: every `blob_t` returned by `load_blob` must be safe to pass to `destroy_blob` exactly once.

